<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911023-0076</DOCNO><DOCID>911023-0076.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Japan Lifts Most Sanctions   Imposed on South Africa   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>10/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10</SO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND ANALYSIS (IEN)TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><RE>AFRICA (AF)FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)SOUTH AFRICA (SF)</RE><LP>   TOKYO -- Japan lifted most of its economic sanctionsagainst South Africa, saying it judged the process ofdismantling apartheid in South Africa &quot;irreversible.&quot;   The sanctions covered a ban on imports of South Africaniron and steel, restriction on investment and financing thereand suspension of air links between Japan and South Africa.Japan also ended its call on Japanese to exhibit&quot;self-restraint&quot; on imports of krugerrands and other goldcoins produced in South Africa.</LP><TEXT>   While the South African government applauded the move, theblack nationalist African National Congress expresseddisappointment at what is called Japan's &quot;hasty&quot; decision.   &quot;We had hoped the government wouldn't lift sanctions untilan interim government has been agreed upon,&quot; said AllyLumkwana, the ANC's deputy chief representative in Tokyo.   The U.S. and the European Community have already liftedsanctions.   The only Japanese sanctions remaining are restriction ofdiplomatic relations on the consular level, a ban on exportof weaponry, and a ban on export of computer products toapartheid enforcement agencies.   Japan's trade with South Africa totaled $3.3 billion lastyear. Japan was South Africa's fourth largest tradingpartner, following Germany, Britain and the U.S.</TEXT></DOC>